{
  "text": "We are interested in how well the small world networks and random networks, trained using the perceptron style learning rule described above, perform as associative memories. The capacity of such networks is determined by the number of incoming connections (k) that each perceptron has. For random pattern sets a perceptron can learn up to 2k patterns [CITATION_1] . Assuming roughly regular connectivity graphs (as is the case here) the capacity will be determined by the level of dilution and not the specific pattern of connections, and hence is not subject to empirical investigation. We use R, the normalised mean radius of the basins of attraction, as a measure of attractor performance in these networks. It is defined as:",
